Week 2: linear regression and model validation

The data used here is derived from an introductory course in social statistics, organised in 2014. The full detailed metadata can be accessed here: https://www.mv.helsinki.fi/home/kvehkala/JYTmooc/JYTOPKYS3-meta.txt.

Inputting data to R

#set working directory
setwd("C:\\Users\\Niko\\Documents\\IODS-project\\data")
learning2014analysis <- read.csv("learning2014analysis.csv", header = T)

The data consists of 7 variables and 166 observations, as explored below in R code.

str(learning2014analysis)
## 'data.frame':    166 obs. of  7 variables:
##  $ age     : int  53 55 49 53 49 38 50 37 37 42 ...
##  $ attitude: int  37 31 25 35 37 38 35 29 38 21 ...
##  $ gender  : Factor w/ 2 levels "F","M": 1 2 1 2 2 1 2 1 2 1 ...
##  $ points  : int  25 12 24 10 22 21 21 31 24 26 ...
##  $ deep    : num  3.58 2.92 3.5 3.5 3.67 ...
##  $ stra    : num  3.38 2.75 3.62 3.12 3.62 ...
##  $ surf    : num  2.58 3.17 2.25 2.25 2.83 ...

attitude is a numerical estimate of the student’s attitude towards statistics, based on a questionnaire. Points are the exam points on the final exam of the course. Age and gender are collected for each participant. Deep, stra and surf are variables about different approaches to statistics: a deep approach (deep), a strategic approach (stra) and a surface approach (surf). The data is derived from questions targeted for each specific approach on a Likert scale (1-5). All question scores for a given approach have been averaged to form a single deep, stra or surf value per correspondent. In the data wrangling section those correspondents without a exam score (points = 0, 17 correspondents) have been excluded.

As we are trying to predict and explain the final exam score, the points -variable is the target variable. Firstly, it seems age has little to do with any of the other variables, however the distribution of ages is skewed to younger ages, as the third quantile is 27 but the maximal age is 55. Similarly gender seems not to have a great impact based on the scatterplots. However, there is twice as many females included in the study group (F = 110, M = 56).

Attitude seems to have the biggest and a positive impact on points, according to the scatterplots, a linear model could be fitted to the data. Attitude seems to be generally higher in males than in females.

It is more difficult to judge if variables deep, surf or stra could act as meaningful explanatory variables for points, stra possibly being the best and slightly positive. Surf could potentially have a negative relationship with points. It is difficult to see a clear pattern between deep and points. However, deep and surf seem to have a negative relationship. This could be an indicator that the questionnaire is actually working in designating approaches to corrspondents: it is intuitive that students assigned to have a deep approach would have lower scores for a surface approach and vice versa. Deep values seem to be higher than other approach variables, and especially skewed towards higher values. Deep seems also to have the biggest outlier visible in the scatterplot matrix (low value of 1.585).

Explanatory variables chosen for the model are attitude, stra and surf, deep is excluded for the outlier, the apparent skew and the lack of pattern with points.

model1 <- lm(points ~ attitude + stra + surf, data = learning2014analysis)
summary(model1)

In this model we see a highly significant effect of attitude, where the estimate for the slope is about 0.34. Significance is analysed with a t-statistic, by performing a t-test against the null hypothesis: “the slope does not differ from 0”. The probability of the null hypothesis is very low (and lower than 0.05), so according to convention we can conclude that a significant result is found. However, both variables stra and surf have non-significant contributions to the model. We shall remove both variables from the final model, and cease any further interpretion of results, since the model will change due to the removal of non-significant explanatory variables. For starts, we remove the variable surf, since it’s p-value is highest.

model2 <- lm(points ~ attitude + stra, data = learning2014analysis)

Here, we still find that the contribution of variable stra is still non-significant, however, the p-value is now considerably lower due to the removal of surf. For the final model, this variable is anyhow removed.

model3 <- lm(points ~ attitude, data = learning2014analysis)
summary(model3)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = points ~ attitude, data = learning2014analysis)
## 
## Residuals:
##      Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max 
## -16.9763  -3.2119   0.4339   4.1534  10.6645 
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept) 11.63715    1.83035   6.358 1.95e-09 ***
## attitude     0.35255    0.05674   6.214 4.12e-09 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 5.32 on 164 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.1906, Adjusted R-squared:  0.1856 
## F-statistic: 38.61 on 1 and 164 DF,  p-value: 4.119e-09

Here the sole explanatory variable attitude is significant. The relationship between points and attitude is a positive one, with a slope of ~0.35. This means that the model estimates for an increase of 1 attitude score, +0.35 points were awarded in the final exam. The y-intercept of the modelled line is estimated at ~11.6 points, significantly different from 0 according to the t-test. The multiple R squared statistic tells us the square of the correlation coefficient between points and attitude. Being ~0.19, it suggests that ~19% of the variation in points is explained by the variation in attitude.

Model validation: diagnostic plots 1. residuals vs. fitted values 2. normal QQ-plot 3. residuals vs. leverage

plot(model3, which = 1) #residuals vs. fitted

plot(model3, which = 2) #Normal QQ-plot

plot(model3, which = 5) #residuals vs. leverage (with Cook's D as a red add-on line)

For residuals vs. fitted values, nothing too alarming is found and the model can be considered valid. There is no clear pattern of residuals, albeit three potential outliers are located in the plot (datapoints 145,56,35). The very high fitted values (>27) seem to have lower residuals, but overall there is no clear pattern. The Normal QQ-plot does show that the data deviates from the assumptions that the data is normally distributed. However, for the majority of the data the QQ-plot is ok for model validation, and the deviating points are few (but include the same outliers discussed above). For now, we could consider the model valid, especially since the significance of the slope was so high. To improve the model, one could try a transformation for the data to improve the normality of the residuals. Nothing alarming is found in the third graph, no datapoint is of high leverage or Cook’s D. This strengthens the assumption that the model is valid, as the outliers mentioned above seem not to have too much of an impact on the actual values of the model parameters.

Alcohol use (high or low) is the target variable, and here we’ll see if explanatory variables provided are related to alcohol use. The chosen explanatory variables include sex, number of school absences, extra-curricular activities (yes or no) and free time after school (from 1 = very low to 5 = very high). The hypotheses are as follows: 1. Males would tend to drink more than females, this seems to be the case for many social groups and settings. 2. High school absences could be associated with high alcohol use 3. Attendance in extra-curricular activities would limit alcohol use 4. High free time after school could indicate that the student would have time and maybe drink more. It is noteworthy to see that if the model does find significant relationships, it does not necessarily imply causality between the variables. For instance if school absences and high alcohol use are significantly related, it does not mean that absences cause high alcohol use nor that high alcohol use causes absences. These variables are statistically related, so they have a relationship but it is not necessarily causal.

Fitting the model:

model1 <- glm(high_use ~ sex + absences + activities + freetime, data = alc, family = "binomial")

Statistical significance can be judged from the model coefficients, and a z-testi is used by default. Here we see that sex, number of absences and amount of free time have all positive and significant effect on high alcohol use. Having extra-curricular activities however has no statistically significant relation to high alcohol use in this data. The significance can also be judged from the confidence intervals of the odds ratio, where 1 is not included in the CI then the effect is significant. Hypotheses: 1. Being male increases the odds of being a high drinker between 1.56 and 4.14 times compared to females. Hypothesis is accepted. 2. Having a lot of absences increases the odds of being a high drinker by between 1.06 and 1.16 times for an incerease of 1 absence. 3. Having extra-curricular activities is less likely for high drinkers, but this effect is not significant in this data. 4. Having more free time increases the odds of being a high drinker between 1.06 and 1.74 times for an increase of 1 on a Likert scale of free time (from 1 = very low to 5 = very high).

Exploring model predictions:

#create a model with all explanatory variables significant
model2 <- glm(high_use ~ sex + absences + freetime, data = alc, family = "binomial")
#predict
probabilities <- predict(model2, type = "response")
alc <- mutate(alc, probability = probabilities)
alc <- mutate(alc, prediction = probability > 0.5)

# 2 x 2 cross-tabulation
table(high_use = alc$high_use, prediction = alc$prediction)
##         prediction
## high_use FALSE TRUE
##    FALSE   254   14
##    TRUE     88   26
#Graphical visualisation of predictions
library(ggplot2)
g <- ggplot(alc, aes(x = probability, y = high_use, col = prediction))
g + geom_point()

#proportion of wrong predictions by using a loss function
loss_func <- function(class, prob) {
  n_wrong <- abs(class - prob) > 0.5
  mean(n_wrong)
}
loss_func(class = alc$high_use, prob = alc$probability)
## [1] 0.2670157

From the training error of about 27 % we can judge that the model is working much better compared to a simple 50/50 guess. 14 + 88 = 102 cases are predicted wrongly, most being correspondents of high alcohol use, but not caught by the model. This could indicate there are more factors affecting alcohol use, so maybe addition of new variables could increase model accuracy. In the graphic we can see a single “true” outlier, but clearly no cutoff is visible in the data where predictions are correct or incorrect.

#10-fold cross-validation
library(boot)
cv <- cv.glm(data = alc, cost = loss_func, glmfit = model2, K = 10)
cv$delta[1]
## [1] 0.2748691

the predictative power of the 10-fold cross validation is similar but lower to the previous model as well as lower than the DataCamp example (error 0.26). The error rises in the cross validation, since less data is used to set up the model. Better models could be found if more predictors are included.

The Boston dataset is included in the R package MASS, and includes data on housing values in suburbs of Boston. What we are most interested here is the per capita crime rate in each of the suburbian towns, and how the towns can be classified according to this variable. The full description of the dataset can be accessed here: https://stat.ethz.ch/R-manual/R-devel/library/MASS/html/Boston.html.

Graphical summary

pairs(Boston)

From the full graphical summary we can see that the data is quite varied, most variables being continuous but some discreet (eg. presence/absence of riverside chas). Some rather clear relationships are visible in the data, eg. between medv and rm (median value of homes and average room number) and dist & tax (distance to employment centres and property tax rate. Relationships can be more easily seen in the correlation matrix below:

cor_matrix<-cor(Boston)
cor_matrix <- round(cor_matrix, digits = 2)

Standardizing data: here, we scale the variables so that means are set to 0, and the variation withing a variable is taken into account via the standard deviation. The scale() function is applicable, since all data is numerical.

library(MASS)
boston_scaled <- scale(Boston)
boston_scaled <- as.data.frame(boston_scaled)

Setting a categorical variable “crime_rate”

library(dplyr)
#create bin vector, use quantiles
bins <- quantile(boston_scaled$crim)
#create new factor variable
crime_rate <- cut(boston_scaled$crim, breaks = bins, include.lowest = TRUE, label = c("low", "med_low", "med_high", "high"))
#drop continuous crime
boston_scaled <- dplyr::select(boston_scaled, -crim)
#insert new factor crime_rate
boston_scaled <- data.frame(boston_scaled, crime_rate)

Splitting data to 80% train set and 20% test set

#take number of rows
n <- nrow(boston_scaled)
#choose 80%
ind <- sample(n,  size = n * 0.8)
# create train set
train <- boston_scaled[ind,]
# create test set 
test <- boston_scaled[-ind,]

Fitting the linear discriminant analysis

lda.fit <- lda(crime_rate ~., data = train)
classes <- as.numeric(train$crime_rate)
plot(lda.fit, dimen = 2, col = classes, pch = classes)

Prediction

#save correct classifications from the test data set for model validation
correct_classes <- test$crime_rate
#drop classifications
test <- dplyr::select(test, -crime_rate)
#prediction
lda.pred <- predict(lda.fit, newdata = test)
#results
table(correct = correct_classes, predicted = lda.pred$class)
##           predicted
## correct    low med_low med_high high
##   low       14      10        0    0
##   med_low    1      18        9    0
##   med_high   0       9       14    1
##   high       0       0        0   26

The model seems to predict the crime categories reasonably well! Most difficult seems to be distinguishing categories med_high and med_low as well as between low and med_low (both with 11 missclassified observations). Notably no observations of the score “high” were predicted to any incorrect category. The full rate of failed classifications is 3+2+11+1+11 = 28 over 74 so about 38%. Not ideal, but still useful.

distance-based k-means

data("Boston")
boston_scaled <- scale(Boston)
boston_scaled <- as.data.frame(boston_scaled)
#calculate euclidean distance matrix
dist_eu <- dist(boston_scaled, method = "euclidean")
#initial k-means with 3 centers
km1 <-kmeans(boston_scaled, centers = 3)
pairs(boston_scaled, col = km1$cluster)

Checking for optimate number of centers with within cluster sum of squares

library(ggplot2)
#set the seed for reproducability
set.seed(123)
#max clusters k = 10
k_max <- 10
#total within sum of squares function
twcss <- sapply(1:k_max, function(k){kmeans(boston_scaled, k)$tot.withinss})
#visualise
qplot(x = 1:k_max, y = twcss, geom = 'line')

Well it is a bit unclear where the best “drop” in TWCSS is, but as very many clusters are quite difficult to deal with, we’ll choose k = 2 here.

km2 <-kmeans(boston_scaled, centers = 2)
pairs(boston_scaled, col = km2$cluster)

As the data is mostly continuous, it is difficult to see visually the clusters separating as clear entities. However, it does seem that majority of the data belongs to one cluster (red in the graphic), whereas the black cluster seem to be the minority of observations. Higher crime rates are associated with the black category.

Bonus

#kmeans for 4 centers for scaled Boston dataset
km3 <- kmeans(boston_scaled, centers = 4)
#include the kmeans clusted in the data frame
boston_scaled$cluster <- km3$cluster
#LDA on clusters
lda.fit2 <- lda(boston_scaled$cluster ~., data = boston_scaled)
#visualise, set up function for LDA arrows
lda.arrows <- function(x, myscale = 1, arrow_heads = 0.1, color = "black", tex = 0.75, choices = c(1,2)){
  heads <- coef(x)
  arrows(x0 = 0, y0 = 0, 
         x1 = myscale * heads[,choices[1]], 
         y1 = myscale * heads[,choices[2]], col=color, length = arrow_heads)
  text(myscale * heads[,choices], labels = row.names(heads), 
       cex = tex, col=color, pos=3)
}

# target classes as numeric
classes <- as.numeric(boston_scaled$cluster)

# plot the lda results
plot(lda.fit2, dimen = 2, col = classes, pch = classes)
lda.arrows(lda.fit2, myscale = 2)

Clusters seem to separate reasonably well in the LDA plot. Arrow length in the plot is proportional to the relative strength of the variable in question affecting the clustering. It seems variables black (1000(Bk - 0.63)^2 where Bk is the proportion of blacks in town, a variable quantifying the ethnic background of the suburbs) and indus (proportion of non-retail business acres per town) seem to be the most influential.
